	<article id="post-259" class="post-259 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized tag-graphical-models tag-machine-learning tag-markov-logic tag-maya tag-programming tag-scala">
				<header class="entry-header">
			<img width="624" height="468" src="http://www.speechlike.org/wp-content/uploads/319269278_a827794043_z-624x468.jpg" class="attachment-post-thumbnail wp-post-image" alt="Photo credit: Joe Robertson" title="Photo credit: Joe Robertson" />						<h1 class="entry-title">Probabilistic programming with undirected graphical models</h1>
					</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<p>&#8220;Probabilistic programming,&#8221; <a href="http://zinkov.com/posts/2012-06-27-why-prob-programming-matters/">blogged Rob Zinkov,</a> &#8220;has the potential to give machine learning to the masses.&#8221; I am living proof that this is true. Thanks to a probabilistic programming language, in spite of my lack of training in probability theory, machine learning, or even <em>college-level math,</em> I have successfully used machine learning techniques to model linguistic data and make predictions.</p>
<p>But the tools that I&#8217;ve found most helpful in coming to grips with machine learning are not discussed much in Zinkov&#8217;s excellent post. Those tools are undirected <a href="https://www.coursera.org/course/pgm">graphical models</a> and the <a href="http://www.morganclaypool.com/doi/abs/10.2200/S00206ED1V01Y200907AIM007">Markov Logic</a> templating language.</p>
<p><span id="more-259"></span></p>
<p>Markov Logic is an expressive and intuitive means of specifying complex joint probability models in terms of weighted first-order logic constraints. Because Markov logic is a close relative of <a href="http://roa.rutgers.edu/">certain theoretical frameworks</a> that are well known in linguistics and cognitive science, it&#8217;s also a uniquely useful didactic device for introducing machine learning concepts to researchers in those disciplines.</p>
<p>As a machine learning outsider, I think Markov Logic is really cool. I can&#8217;t help but notice, though, that implementations of Markov Logic are no longer being actively developed. Why? What flaws have caused machine learning insiders to lose enthusiasm for it? What other toolkits are out there for working with undirected graphical models?</p>
<h2>Markov Logic and its implementations</h2>
<p>Sometime late in 2012, I gave an informal presentation to the Cornell Computational Linguistics Lab about Markov Logic and the use I had been making of it for modeling unaccusativity in Maya. I&#8217;ve posted <a href="http://nmashton.ca/pdf/mlntalk.pdf">the slides from that presentation</a> (7.9 mb PDF), which include the notes I used to give the talk. Check out those slides if you want to see my take on what Markov Logic is about. [Edit 29-01-13: I've decided not to host the slides on SlideShare.]</p>
<p>To put it country simple: an undirected graphical model is a way of modeling an uncertain situation that has subparts that may be entangled with one another. Markov Logic is a means of specifying families of undirected graphical models with weighted formulas of first-order logic. It&#8217;s similar in an obvious and non-misleading way to the frameworks of Harmonic Grammar and Optimality Theory which many linguists are familiar with. Implementations of Markov Logic allow you to learn models from data and to use them to make predictions.</p>
<p>As I say in my slides, I&#8217;ve been relying on the <a href="http://alchemy.cs.washington.edu/">Alchemy</a> implementation of Markov Logic. I can&#8217;t help but notice that Alchemy hasn&#8217;t been updated since 2010 (even though <a href="http://scholar.google.com/scholar?as_ylo=2012&amp;q=%22markov+logic%22&amp;hl=en&amp;as_sdt=0,33">a Google Scholar search</a> shows that interest in Markov Logic is still quite lively). Other implementations do exist: there&#8217;s also <a href="http://code.google.com/p/thebeast/">markov thebeast</a> and <a href="http://hazy.cs.wisc.edu/hazy/tuffy/">Tuffy</a>. But those also appear to be dead, last updated respectively in 2010 and 2011.</p>
<p>What gives?</p>
<h2>Other languages for undirected graphical models</h2>
<p>There are other probabilistic programming languages—<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domain-specific_language">DSLs</a>, really—that let you work with the same kinds of models as Markov Logic. At least one of them seems to be under active development, as of January 2013.</p>
<p>The strange thing is: they all seem to be <a href="http://www.scala-lang.org">Scala</a> libraries. Foremost among these Scala libraries is <a href="https://sites.google.com/site/factoriesite/">Factorie</a>, which is the work of <a href="http://people.cs.umass.edu/~mccallum/">Andrew McCallum</a> and his collaborators. Whereas Markov Logic offers a declarative, logical approach to specifying undirected graphical models, Factorie offers the exact opposite: with Factorie, you describe models in imperative-programming style. Other Scala libraries for undirected graphical modeling include the commercial package <a href="https://www.cra.com/commercial-solutions/probabilistic-modeling-services.asp">Figaro</a> (hidden behind a menacing contact information form) and Sebastian Riedel&#8217;s <a href="http://www.riedelcastro.org/fast-froward/">fast-froward</a> (sic).</p>
<p>I don&#8217;t know Scala, and I haven&#8217;t used any of these libraries, so I have nothing to say about any of them. Do you, dear reader? Please leave comments telling me about these and any other undirected graphical model DSLs or languages you&#8217;ve worked with.</p>
<p>Now, I do wonder <em>why</em> Scala is the universal medium of undirected graphical modeling libraries—surely nothing about Scala particularly lends itself to the task?—but the fact that it <em>is</em> may have finally pushed my curiosity over the tipping point and convinced me to learn some Scala.</p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
