		<article id="comment-227" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/2d04526219dad642271c8757ebea0c32?s=44&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D44&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite class="fn">Larysa </cite><a href="http://www.speechlike.org/2013/01/probabilistic-programming-with-undirected-graphical-models/#comment-227"><time pubdate datetime="2013-01-29T15:00:48+00:00">January 29, 2013 at 15:00</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Hi Neil,<br />
as long as there are such enthusiasts, and people passionate about Markov Logic, this tool remains popular. <img src='http://www.speechlike.org/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt=':)' class='wp-smiley' />  I suppose that the current silence about Alchemy development is because some people, which were involved into development got their PhDs and left the university. (I am talking about H.Poon and F.Niu)<br />
The second reason could be the fact that Alchemy does not really scale to the realistic data sets.  Sometimes it takes ages to run  weight/structure learning on simple classification. And we need to figure out how to do learning/inference at reasonable scale and pace.<br />
It seems that P.Domingos and his research group are working on Tractable Markov Logic (<a href="http://homes.cs.washington.edu/~pedrod/papers/aaai12.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://homes.cs.washington.edu/~pedrod/papers/aaai12.pdf</a>) in order to be able to model large systems and perform tractable inference on it. The implementation of TML should be available soon: <a href="http://alchemy.cs.washington.edu/lite/" rel="nofollow">http://alchemy.cs.washington.edu/lite/</a></p>
<p>Concerning Scala, I have my theory that this is because of the scientists solidarity <img src='http://www.speechlike.org/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_wink.gif' alt=';)' class='wp-smiley' /> &#8230; since Scala was developed and promoted from/within an academic community&#8230;.</p>
<p>I am accidentally in the computational linguistic and after trying to model linguistic data with statistical methods, I was immediately convinced by statistical relational learning (and Markov Logic in particular)&#8230;. However, after looking for an intuitive/working framework I have decided to implement Markov Logic by myself <img src='http://www.speechlike.org/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt=':)' class='wp-smiley' /> &#8230;.. in Clojure&#8230;. because I believe we have to use the right tool for the job, and in case of language modelling Markov Logic is perfect&#8230;. Clojure &#8211; is self explained.</p>
<p>Best,<br />
Larysa</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

