	<li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-232">
		<article id="comment-232" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/65e01b488da1fa55ea88ad99e78cb7ea?s=44&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D44&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.iit.demokritos.gr/~anskarl' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Anastasios Skarlatidis</a> </cite><a href="http://www.speechlike.org/2013/01/probabilistic-programming-with-undirected-graphical-models/#comment-232"><time pubdate datetime="2013-01-30T06:18:20+00:00">January 30, 2013 at 06:18</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>The scalability is a common issue to all Statistical Relational Learning methods (e.g. Markov Logic and ProbLog). Usually, before inference, grounding must be performed. Even with relatively small knowledge-bases, in large (realistic) domains grounding may be the biggest bottleneck. I think that the problem is both theoretical and technical (implementation). For example, depending on the given evidence/facts all tautological clauses can be safely ruled out as they remain satisfied in all possible worlds (i.e. Herbrand iterpretations), e.g.  <a href="http://www.aaai.org/ocs/index.php/IJCAI/IJCAI-09/paper/viewFile/346/843" rel="nofollow">http://www.aaai.org/ocs/index.php/IJCAI/IJCAI-09/paper/viewFile/346/843</a> . From technical perspective, the MLN can be stored in a relational DB, e.g. the Tuffy toolkit, and during the inference only a small part of the MLN may be loaded in the memory. A different approach is to avoid complete grounding and employ lifted inference methods, e.g. <a href="http://www.hlt.utdallas.edu/~vgogate/papers/uai11-b.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.hlt.utdallas.edu/~vgogate/papers/uai11-b.pdf</a> and <a href="https://lirias.kuleuven.be/bitstream/123456789/308265/1/vdb-ijcai11.pdf" rel="nofollow">https://lirias.kuleuven.be/bitstream/123456789/308265/1/vdb-ijcai11.pdf</a> (Scala implementation).</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

