	<li class="comment byuser comment-author-nmashton bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-251">
		<article id="comment-251" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/bdeb778cd2db9acbb6f0b3d69d56adbf?s=44&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D44&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite class="fn">nmashton <span> Post author</span></cite><a href="http://www.speechlike.org/2013/01/probabilistic-programming-with-undirected-graphical-models/#comment-251"><time pubdate datetime="2013-02-01T11:03:35+00:00">February 1, 2013 at 11:03</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Markov Logic (in its Alchemy implementation) is my first and, so far, only experience with probabilistic programming. &#8230; well, technically, I attended a workshop on <a href="http://projects.csail.mit.edu/church/wiki/Church" rel="nofollow">Church</a> at the start of my grad school career, but it went miles over my head at the time. If you&#8217;re interested in <i>generative</i> modeling and like Scheme, you might be interested in Church.</p>
<p>The only non-trivial model I&#8217;ve made so far is my model of unaccusativity in Maya. The code and data are both in a pretty grubby and embarrassing condition, so I haven&#8217;t put them online yet—but I might do so before the end of the school year.</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2013/01/probabilistic-programming-with-undirected-graphical-models/?replytocom=251#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-251", "251", "respond", "259")'>Reply <span>&darr;</span></a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li>
