</li>
	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="li-comment-244">
		<article id="comment-244" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/e0ed34db4c3e433e42b36b697f953332?s=44&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D44&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.riedelcastro.org/' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Sebastian</a> </cite><a href="http://www.speechlike.org/2013/01/probabilistic-programming-with-undirected-graphical-models/#comment-244"><time pubdate datetime="2013-01-31T15:11:33+00:00">January 31, 2013 at 15:11</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Happy to see some SRL enthusiasts out there! </p>
<p>It&#8217;s true that both thebeast and fast-froward aren&#8217;t being actively developed right now. Plus, ff never left the proof-of-concept phase anyway. The main reason for this was my work with Andrew McCallum on FACTORIE for the last years&#8212;there wasn&#8217;t really place for my own &#8220;baby.&#8221; Now that I got a new job, I am very keen on getting back to this though. I think I learned a few lessons that will be helpful in building a better platform.</p>
<p>As a side, while thebeast isn&#8217;t being developed anymore, it may still be a interesting alternative over alchemy, in particular in NLP settings. There are a few catches, it has less features and a weirder syntax, but many folks told me that for their NLP applications it just scales much better. </p>
<p>Why Scala? Personally it&#8217;s a combination of a few things: (1) it&#8217;s generally a powerful language that makes coding easier (and more fun) for me, regardless of the actual application; (2) it&#8217;s DSL support is quite convenient for specifying models, formulas etc.; (3) better suited for concurrency and any kind of parallel inference. This is all relative to what I used before (mostly Java). That being said, there are of course alternatives out there for which this also holds. The reason I ended up with Scala is that Andrew McCallum started to play around with Scala at the time I joined the lab. I think in many cases it may be a matter of &#8220;better than Java, but still close enough&#8221; that made it attractive for ML and NLP folks already working with Java at the time.</p>
<p>I&#8217;d be curious to see how you get on with a Clojure implementation.  Other than being implemented in Clojure, what other kinds of things would you guys want from an SRL language? Or the biggest issue with what&#8217;s out there (other than not being actively developed, or scalability)?</p>
<p>Cheers,</p>
<p>Sebastian</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2013/01/probabilistic-programming-with-undirected-graphical-models/?replytocom=244#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-244", "244", "respond", "259")'>Reply <span>&darr;</span></a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
