	<li class="comment odd alt depth-2" id="li-comment-250">
		<article id="comment-250" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/2d04526219dad642271c8757ebea0c32?s=44&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D44&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite class="fn">Larysa </cite><a href="http://www.speechlike.org/2013/01/probabilistic-programming-with-undirected-graphical-models/#comment-250"><time pubdate datetime="2013-02-01T09:49:29+00:00">February 1, 2013 at 09:49</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Hi all,</p>
<p>I think the most important issue is the (1) unified declarative interface (think about SQL for datatases) which will be implemented by different engines. Alchemy is the first attempt to introduce such an interface for AI and first-order logic formulae might be the right choice. But I am looking for an intuitive and declarative DSL for SRL, where I can define models and run the inference.</p>
<p>(2) Promoting SRL is the another point, because somehow I got an impression that Markov Logic is still a &#8220;secrete-hammer-for-scientists&#8221;.Has someone heard about end-to-end SRL systems used in the industry? In commercial projects? (Ok, Neil, you are an exception <img src='http://www.speechlike.org/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt=':)' class='wp-smiley' />  ) SRL is an very promising area and need more promotion. We need more books, blogs or online-courses about this.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ll let you all know about my progress in Clojure implementation for Markov Logic (disclaimer: I am very newbie in Clojure but really keen on to be proficient <img src='http://www.speechlike.org/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.gif' alt=':)' class='wp-smiley' />  ).</p>
<p>Larysa</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

