	<li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="li-comment-248">
		<article id="comment-248" class="comment">
			<header class="comment-meta comment-author vcard">
				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/65e01b488da1fa55ea88ad99e78cb7ea?s=44&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D44&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.iit.demokritos.gr/~anskarl' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Anastasios Skarlatidis</a> </cite><a href="http://www.speechlike.org/2013/01/probabilistic-programming-with-undirected-graphical-models/#comment-248"><time pubdate datetime="2013-02-01T02:48:15+00:00">February 1, 2013 at 02:48</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Hello,</p>
<p>I think that it is time to combine many ideas from all SRL toolkits into one modular project. It would be great to see one big SRL software based on mature and solid technologies that can take advantage of multiple processing units for scalability (e.g. Actor or Hadoop model).</p>
<p>@Sebastian: I agree with you about the choice of Scala programming language. Compared to Java language, Scala has many benefits (functional, concurrency, more productive) and at the same time it is fully compatible with Java and runs on top of the JVM. About concurrency, for example, I have experimented with an alternative and highly concurrent implementation of MLN grounding in Scala (FYI the experimental-and-incomplete  toolkit is called LoMRF).  The grounding process employs the Actor model (Akka library), in order to ground each clause concurrently. Compared to Alchemy, the parallel grounding is much more faster and the difference grows in larger domains and complex knowledge bases.  </p>
<p>Best,</p>
<p>Anastasios</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

